headline: Winter Olympics in Sochi
In or about this year, one person returning to Haiti from the Congo is thought to have first brought HIV to the Americas.
August 3 - Christopher Columbus sails the ocean blue on his first journey across the Atlantic Ocean to Asia, but he ends up in the Americas
April 25 - Martin Waldseem�ller publishes his world map, naming the new continent America in honour of Amerigo Vespucci (However, the accuracy of this is still debated).
May 12 - The National University of San Marcos is founded in Lima (Peru), being the first officially established university in the Americas.
July 30 - In Jamestown, Virginia, the first representative assembly in the Americas, the House of Burgesses, convenes for the first time.
November 9 - At least 50 people are killed and more than 120 injured in a series of coordinated suicide bombings in Amman, Jordan (See 2005 Amman bombings).
Fighting breaks out between Arab guerillas and government forces in Amman, Jordan.

The Byzantine emperor Theophilos is heavily defeated at the Battle of Anzen by the Abbasids. Caliph al-Mu'tasim then proceeds to capture and raze Amorium, the native city of the Byzantine Empire's reigning Amorian dynasty.

Byzantine Empire: March?The Umayyads under Maslamah ibn Abd al-Malik capture and sack the Byzantine city of Tyana after a prolonged siege, and following a victory over a Byzantine relief army. Maslamah also leads another expedition in the summer, and defeats a Byzantine force near Amorium.Stanford, CA  isbn = 0-8047-2630-2  url = http://books.google.com/books?id=nYbnr5XVbzUC  page=341}}<
June 5 - The Indian government begins Operation Blue Star, the planned attack on the Golden Temple in Amritsar.
June 6 - Indian troops storm the Golden Temple at Amritsar, the Sikhs' holiest shrine, killing an estimated 2,000 people.
The tea house Mellow Yellow opens on the Amstel River in Amsterdam, pioneering the legal sale of cannabis in the Netherlands.
In Korea, Anapji was constructed by order of King Munmu.
The Seljuk Turks storm Anatolia, taking Caesarea and Ani, marking the beginning of Turkish incursions into Anatolia.
The first civil revolt in Anatolia takes place, led by Alevi preacher Cel�l.
The Ottomans take Philadelphia, the last Byzantine enclave of any significance in Anatolia.
December 27 - The 1939 Erzincan earthquake in Eastern Anatolia, Turkey, kills 30,000.
Osman I, founder of the Ottoman Empire, becomes ''bey'' of the S�g�t tribe in central Anatolia; in 1299 he will declare independence from the Seljuk Turks, marking the birth of the Ottoman Empire.
The Goths, coming from Ukraine, cross the Danube and devastate the Roman Empire up to the border with Anatolia.
Publius Cornelius Tacitus is Governor of the Roman province of Asia, Anatolia.
Battle of Akroinon in Anatolia, a significant Byzantine victory over the Umayyads, halts the impetus of Arab attacks into Anatolia.
October - Mongol commander Baiju (operating under Hulagu Khan's command) leads his forces in a victory over Kay Ka'us II of the Sultanate of R�m, thereby capturing Anatolia.

Sayf al-Daula leads 30,000 men in a raid into Byzantine Anatolia. He defeats Bardas Phokas, but is then ambushed on his return and heavily defeated by Leo Phokas.Stanford, CA  isbn = 978-0-8047-2630-2  url = http://books.google.com/?id=nYbnr5XVbzUC  pages = 489}}<
A Romano-Celtic{{Citation neededdate=January 2010}} temple-mausoleum complex is constructed in what is now Lullingstone, and also in Anderitum (approximate date).
January 25 - Norwegian rocket incident: A rocket launched from the space exploration centre at And�ya, Norway is briefly interpreted by the Russians as an incoming attack.
March 15 - The Liverpool Football Club is founded by John Houlding, the owner of Anfield. Houlding decides to form his own team after Everton leaves Anfield in an argument over rent.
Jayavarman IV succeeds Isanavarman II in the Khmer Empire, and moves the capital north from Angkor to Koh Ker.
March 17 - Taiping Rebellion: A Taiping army of 350,000 invades Anhui.

March 24 - Taiping Rebellion: Suspecting treachery on the part of East King Yang Xiuqing, Shi Dakai garrisons Anhui and begins his march back to the Heavenly Capital, having defeated a strong Xiang Army dettachment.
Each family holding colonized land in Anhui province has to plant 200 each of mulberry, jujube and persimmon trees

Anjou is conquered by Philip II of France.  Fearing a French invasion of England itself, John of England requires every English male over 12 to enter an association for the general defence of the realm and the preservation of peace.
October 20 - Philip of Anjou, Titular Emperor of Constantinople, marries Elisabeth of Slavonia, daughter of Stephen, duke of Transylvania and Slavonia, and Margareta of Bavaria.
Odo, Count of Paris becomes Count of Anjou on the death of Hugh the Abbot.
April - Philip of Anjou marries Mary of Naples, daughter of Charles of Valois, duke of Calabria, and Mary of Valois.
With the death of Duke Charles IV of Anjou, Anjou reverts to the French crown under Louis XI of France.

February 26 - Battle of Benevento: The army of Charles, Count of Anjou, defeats a combined German and Sicilian force led by King Manfred of Sicily.  Manfred is killed in the battle and Pope Clement IV invests Charles as king of Sicily and Naples.
August 9 ? In the Comoros, the Military Committee of Major Mohamad Bacar seizes power in the island of Anjouan, which had declared independence. They plan to rejoin the Comoros.
February 23 - Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah �calan is charged with treason in Ankara, Turkey.
Raymond IV of Toulouse, count of Tripoli, takes Ankara from the Seljuk Turks.
April 26 - The government of Turkey declares a state of siege in 11 provinces, Ankara included, due to violent demonstrations.
November 15 - Middle East Technical University is founded in Ankara, Turkey.
June 3 - Annapurna I, 10th highest mountain in the world, is first ascended.

March 17 - The President of Madagascar, Marc Ravalomanana, is overthrown in a ''coup d'�tat'', following a month of rallies in Antananarivo. The military appoints opposition leader Andry Rajoelina as the new president.BBC Newsaccessdate= 17 March 2009}}<
July 21 - The lowest temperature on earth is recorded in Vostok Station, Antarctica with ?89.2 ﾰC (?128.6 ﾰF).
January 20 - Dumont D'Urville discovers Ad�lie Land, Antarctica.

December 1 - Cold War - Antarctic Treaty: 12 countries, including the United States and the Soviet Union, sign a landmark treaty, which sets aside Antarctica as a scientific preserve and bans military activity on that continent (the first arms control agreement established during the Cold War).
November 28 - Air New Zealand Flight 901: an Air New Zealand DC-10 crashes into Mount Erebus (in Antarctica) on a sightseeing trip, killing all 257 people on board.
January 19 - Captain Charles Wilkes circumnavigates Antarctica, claiming what becomes known as Wilkes Land for the United States.
At 6:50 PM, a volcano erupts on Deception Island in Antarctica.

Autumn?winter?The Byzantine general Heraclius, brother of Tiberius III, launches a campaign into Syria, defeats an army from Antioch and raids as far as Samosata.Stanford, CA  isbn = 0-8047-2630-2  url = http://books.google.com/books?id=nYbnr5XVbzUC  page=339}}<
Late May (probably between the 20th and the 29th)?An earthquake kills approximately 250,000 in Syria and Antioch.
August 14 - Battle of Hab: Baldwin II of Jerusalem's Crusaders defeat Ilghazi's army, saving Antioch.
Natural disaster: An earthquake strikes Antioch, killing thousands, and causing a fire that destroys the Great Church built by Constantine I.
Alexander Severus assembled the Roman army and establish his headquarters at Antioch. He makes an attempt for diplomatic solutions, but the Persians decline and choose for war.
The disciples of Jesus form communities after the Diaspora, especially in Damascus and Antioch.  For the first time they are called Christians.
Battle of Issus: Emperor Septimius Severus marches with his army (12 legions) to Cilicia and defeats Pescennius Niger, governor of Syria. He retreats to Antioch and  is executed by Severus' troops.
The Sassanid king, Shapur I, orders an invasion of the Roman East with the intent of finally capturing the jewel of Syria, Antioch (251?254).

28 October?Byzantine general Michael Bourtzes seizes part of Antioch's fortifications. The capture of the city from the Arabs is completed three days later, when reinforcements under Peter Phokas arrive.
October 22?The temple of Apollo at Daphne, outside Antioch, is destroyed in a mysterious fire.

Sayf al-Daula raids into the Byzantine theme of Lykandos but is defeated. The Byzantines counter-attack and seize Germanikeia, defeating an army from Tarsus, and the raiding as far south as Antioch. Theophilos Kourkouas captures Theodosiopolis for Byzantium.Stanford, CA  isbn = 978-0-8047-2630-2  url = http://books.google.com/?id=nYbnr5XVbzUC  page = 489}}<
March 5?Emperor Julian moves from Antioch with an army of 90,000 against the Sassanid Empire.

Plotinus, Greek philosopher, escapes the bloodshed that accompanies the murder of Gordianus III and makes his way to Antioch. Back to Rome he founds his Neoplatonist school and attracts students like Porphyry, Castricius Firmus and Eustochius of Alexandria.
The Eastern Orthodox Patriarchy of Antioch returns to Antioch after a 171-year exile, during which it had been replaced by the Latin Patriarch of Antioch.

May 18 - The Principality of Antioch, a crusader state, falls to the Mamluk Sultan Baibars in the Battle of Antioch; Baibars' destruction of the city of Antioch is so great as to permanently negate the city's importance.

A rebellion breaks out against William II of Sicily, and the Byzantine Empire, encouraged by Pope Hadrian, invades Apulia.   William II crushes the rebellion, defeats the Byzantine armies at Brindisi, and humbles the Pope at Benevento.
